Dubai Shares Rise to 2-Week High Before U.S. Data; Oil Advances

-- B y   A l a a   S h a h i n e
-- 
2011-07-07T09:20:39Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-07/dubai-shares-rise-to-2-week-high-before-u-s-data-oil-advances.html
Dubai’s shares rose to the highest
level in two weeks, pacing gains in the  Persian Gulf , before a
report on U.S. jobs and as oil advanced.  Drake & Scull International (DSI)  PJSC, a construction company,
surged to the highest in two weeks. Dubai Islamic Bank, the
biggest Shairah-compliant bank in the United Arab Emirates, rose
1.5 percent. The  DFM General Index (DFMGI)  gained 0.7 percent to
1,562.75 at 12:57 p.m. in the emirate, the highest intraday
level since June 22. The measure rose 3 percent this week. The
Bloomberg BGCC200 Index, which tracks the biggest 200 companies
in the Gulf, advanced 0.7 percent this week.  “Regional markets are gaining direction from international
news flows and international markets performance,” said  Marwan Shurrab , assistant  fund manager  and chief trader at Dubai-based
Gulfmena Alternative Investments.  European stocks advanced for the eighth time in nine days
and futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index expiring in
September gained 0.4 percent. The number of Americans making
initial claims for jobless benefits fell to 420,000 last week
from 428,000 the prior period, according to a Bloomberg News
survey of economists. The data comes a day before the Labor
Department’s monthly payrolls report.  Oil Gains  Oil rose from a two-day low in  New York  as investors bet
declining stockpiles and signs of economic recovery in the U.S.
indicated fuel demand is strengthening in the world’s biggest
crude consumer.  Crude for August delivery gained as much as 1 percent to
$97.62 a barrel in electronic trading on the  New York Mercantile
Exchange . The six nations of the Gulf Cooperation Council,
including the U.A.E. and Saudi Arabia, supply about a fifth of
the world’s oil.  About 74 million shares were traded in Dubai today,
compared with a 12-month daily average of 122 million shares,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Drake & Scull gained 1.8 percent to 99.8 fils, the highest
intraday level since June 21. Dubai Islamic Bank climbed to 2.06
dirhams. Each dirham has 100 fils.  Oman’s benchmark stock index gained 0.4 percent. Kuwait’s
gauge rose 0.1 percent and Bahrain’s measure added 0.1 percent.
Qatar’s  QE Index (DSM)  advanced 0.1 percent, while  Abu Dhabi ’s  ADX
General Index (ADSMI)  was little changed. Saudi Arabia’s market is
closed for the weekend.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Alaa Shahine in Dubai at 
